As the modern era of combination antiretroviral therapy has increased life 
expectancy for individuals infected with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV), 
type 2 diabetes mellitus and disorders of glucose metabolism have emerged as an 
important issue in the care of this population. Multiple mechanisms, both 
specific and nonspecific to HIV, underlie a significant prevalence. Although 
best-practice diagnostic testing remains unclear, the risks associated with 
diabetes in the setting of HIV are well characterized, ranging from 
organ-specific damage to socioeconomic decline. As population-specific treatment 
data are limited, current guidelines serve as a basis for ongoing management.

